menu "breadboard: bb_health"

config BB_HEALTH_STACK_LOW_BYTES
    int "Stack low-water threshold (bytes)"
    default 256
    range 64 65536
    help
        Free stack bytes below which a task is flagged as low. This is a
        near-overflow danger threshold: a task within ~256 B (64 words) of
        overflowing its stack. The old default of 512 B over-warned because
        fixed-depth system tasks (ipc0, ipc1, bb_log_writer) normally run
        at ~500 B high-water and are not in danger. 256 B fires only when
        a task is genuinely close to overflow. Still tunable via
        CONFIG_BB_HEALTH_STACK_LOW_BYTES.

        A health.stack event posts on the first scan where a task crosses
        below this threshold (transition into low), not on every scan, to
        avoid spamming the event bus. The periodic scan itself is owned by
        bb_task_registry (task-registry unification PR3) --
        CONFIG_BB_TASK_REGISTRY_BASE_POLL_MS sets its cadence and
        CONFIG_BB_TASK_BASE_MAX its tracked-task capacity; this component is
        a pure observer of that scan's low-stack transition callback.

        Strongly recommended: also set
          CONFIG_FREERTOS_CHECK_STACKOVERFLOW_PTRVAL=y
        (CONFIG_FREERTOS_CHECK_STACKOVERFLOW=2) so a real overflow prints
        an attributable task-name message instead of a silent abort.

config BB_HEALTH_STACK_AUTOSTART
    bool "Auto-register the low-stack observer with bb_task_registry at PRE_HTTP"
    default y
    depends on FREERTOS_USE_TRACE_FACILITY
    help
        When enabled, bb_health_stack_monitor_start registers this
        component's low-stack transition handler with bb_task_registry
        (bb_task_registry_set_low_stack_handler) at the pre_http registry
        tier. Disable to call bb_health_stack_monitor_start manually before
        bb_health_stack_monitor_init.

config BB_HEALTH_SECTION_TABLE_CAP
    int "Composer section registry table capacity (bb_health_section, B1-1096)"
    default 8
    range 1 16
    help
        Fixed table capacity for the bb_health_section composer registry
        (components/bb_health/include/bb_health_section.h) -- distinct from
        the legacy bb_health_register_section()/BB_RESPONSE_MAX registry.
        Default 8 matches today's BB_RESPONSE_MAX. ADDITIVE AND INERT in
        this PR -- nothing consumes this registry yet (B1-1096, epic
        B1-1054).

config BB_HEALTH_SECTION_SCRATCH_BYTES
    int "Composer section per-section render scratch buffer size (bytes)"
    default 128
    range 32 1024
    help
        Size of the stack buffer the future bb_health composer (B1-1054
        PR-5) fills one section's snapshot into before rendering it.
        bb_health_section_register() rejects (BB_ERR_NO_SPACE) any section
        whose snap_desc->snap_size exceeds this bound at registration time.
        Default 128 is measured, not padded: the largest known snapshot
        today is 32 B (bb_mqtt_client_health_snap_t and its bb_tcp_client/
        bb_http_client siblings); 128 B is 4x headroom over that. The
        composer's real worst-case path -- the full
        BB_HEALTH_SECTION_TABLE_CAP x BB_HEALTH_SECTION_SCRATCH_BYTES arena
        (1024 B) plus the bb_serialize_json flush buffer (768 B) plus
        root/entries overhead (~200 B), roughly 2 KB total -- fits
        CONFIG_BB_HTTP_TASK_STACK_SIZE's (6144 B) budget checked on this
        composer's own path independently -- the WS-connect snapshot
        path's ~3.5 KB claim is a SEPARATE, sequential top-level route
        dispatch on the same task type, an alternate peak rather than a
        shared claim to subtract -- see bb_health_section_priv.h's
        BB_HEALTH_SECTION_SCRATCH_BYTES comment for the full arithmetic.

endmenu
